content.description:
The FA, Jeff Jackson, called it a " Stacked formation". It is difficult to see from the trail due to the heavy vegetation growth since the early 90's. 

  Hasn't been climbed in years.
content.protection: None. A free solo by Jeff BITD
content.location: Located about 100 feet to the right of Hanks. Buried in the trees. I have TRed the route by 4th class access on the left side and using long ( 60') webbing to sling a boulder

content.description: Easy, open climbing up until above the third bolt. The crux, which is significantly harder than the rest of the route, earns the 10d rating (at least) and occurs between the last (fifth) bolt and the anchor chains. Belayers be careful of loose belays above the fifth bolt, as the ledge beneath the fourth presents a mild fall hazard. Anchor holds may be chossy/flakey, so get yourself certain before pulling out clip slack.         This route can also be top-roped by traversing left from the anchor chains of the route immediately to its right.

Starts with about 15 feet of slab climbing with a bolt at the end of the slab. Work your way up past some ledges.  Feels like 5.8+ until the last bolt.  Super fun route. Slightly runout at the beginning.  Definitely worth it.
content.location: This is the first wall on your right when coming from the Spyglass entrance. After walking past the wooden fence and zigzagging through some boulders, the wall is about 100 feet on your right.

content.description: Going straight up after the second bolt provides for the full experience of this four bolt line protected at the top by chains
Rarely climbed, strong sun from late morning to late afternoon.
